            <div>

	<!-- Change both @facs and @n below -->
	<!-- Start each page with a <pb> formatted as below -->               
	<pb facs="liv_001693_0001" n="0001"/>

<!-- If this is a letter or similar with an opener (with content such as dateline and/or salute) add it. For example: -->
<opener>
<lb/><space extent="7" unit="words"/><add place="inspace" rend="gray small" hand="#U">ms 8/7</add> 
<lb/><dateline rend="right"><placeName><geogName type="river">River Shire</geogName></placeName> <date when="1861-11-18">18<hi rend="sup underline">th</hi> <choice><abbr>Nov<hi rend="sup underline">r</hi></abbr><expan>November</expan></choice> 1861</date></dateline>
<lb/>
<lb/><space extent="2" unit="chars"/><hi rend="underline">Private</hi>    
<lb/><space extent="2" unit="chars"/><salute>My Dear Sunley,</salute>
</opener>

<lb/><p><space extent="3" unit="words"/>We went up to <placeName><geogName type="lake">Lake
<lb/>Nyasa</geogName></placeName> by carrying a boat past the
<lb/>cataracts of this river intending to find out<!-- geog: Cataracts of River Shire -->
<lb/>more about the <placeName><geogName type="river">Rovuma</geogName></placeName> from above
<lb/>than we could from below, but we
<lb/>were unsuccessful - We were on the 
<lb/>Lake during the <seg type="weather">Equinoctial gales</seg><!-- geog: Lake Nyassa -->
<lb/>and like all narrow seas surrounded
<lb/>with mountains tremendous seas
<lb/>get up in a quarter of an hour or 
<lb/>twenty mintues - We went up the 
<lb/>Western shore and the frequency of<!-- geog: Western shore of Lake Nyassa -->
<lb/><seg type="weather">storms</seg> in which no open boat
<lb/>could live prevented our crossing &amp;
<lb/>finding out all about <placeName><geogName type="river">Rovuma</geogName></placeName>
<lb/>Reports were rife enough from the
<lb/>positive assertion that we could sail
<lb/>from the Lake into the River to the</p><!-- geog: Lake Nyassa --><!-- geog: Rovuma River -->

<cb rend="vertical"/>
<ab>
<lb/>Do you know where a place called by the <orgName>Arabs</orgName> <placeName>Shamo</placeName>
<lb/><space extent="2" unit="chars"/>is?
</ab> 

	<pb facs="liv_001693_0002" n="0002"/>
<lb/><p rend="no-indent">equaly positive statement that we must
<lb/>carry it a month - We found the Lake to be<!-- geog: Lake Nyassa -->
<lb/>very deep - no bottom at <measure><measure>116 fathoms</measure> a <measure>mile</measure>
<lb/>out</measure> - and generally a ship must be near
<lb/>shore to find anchorage - Width from <measure>20 
<lb/>to 50 or 60 miles</measure> - <space extent="1" unit="chars"/>Length over <measure>200</measure>
<lb/>Its northern end is <measure><choice><abbr>Lat</abbr><expan>Latitude</expan></choice> 10ยบ South</measure> - -<!-- geog: northern end of Lake Nyassa -->
<lb/>An <orgName>Arab</orgName> dhow has lately been built on 
<lb/>it to supply, we suppose, the trade at <placeName><settlement type="village">Iboe</settlement></placeName>.
<lb/>It fled from us twice and we could
<lb/>not cross to the East side to look at it.<!-- geog: East Side of Lake Nyassa -->
<lb/>We heard that <persName>Ben Habib</persName> the <orgName>Arab</orgName> who
<lb/>abducted 95 <term type="tribe"><choice><orig>Makololo</orig><reg>Kololo</reg></choice></term> had gone back
<lb/>in a great hurry, we suspect stirred 
<lb/>up by <persName><choice><abbr>Col</abbr><expan>Colonel</expan></choice> Rigby</persName> - He has had them
<lb/>away seven years - Your <orgName><placeName><geogName type="island">Johanna</geogName></placeName> 
<lb/>men</orgName> have turned out very well -
<lb/>they are better than the <term type="tribe"><choice><orig>Kroomen</orig><corr>Kurumen</corr></choice></term> we
<lb/>formaly had - they have been most
<lb/>of their time at the foot of the cataracts<!-- geog: Cataracts of the River Shire -->
<lb/>where <term type="plant_foodstuff">rice</term> is not to be had, but <term type="foodstuff">meal</term>
<lb/>seems to go down with them - I did
<lb/>not take them up to <placeName><geogName type= "lake">Nyasa</geogName></placeName> as

	<pb facs="liv_001693_0003" n="0003"/>
<lb/>they were required to guard the ship -
<lb/>If you can engage twelve or fourteen
<lb/>I could do better with them than with some
<lb/>of the whites who are frequently ill - If I
<lb/><choice><sic>I</sic><corr/></choice> cannot come to <placeName><geogName type="island">Johanna</geogName></placeName> I shall send
<lb/>these by man of war - At present they
<lb/>are all well, and do not express any
<lb/>anxiety about returning -</p>
<lb/><p>I met two <orgName><placeName><geogName><geogName type="island">Zanzibar</geogName></geogName></placeName> <orgName>Arabs</orgName></orgName> who
<lb/>had come down from <placeName><region>Katanga</region></placeName> in the
<lb/>far interior to buy cloth at <placeName><geogName type="lake">Nyasa</geogName></placeName>
<lb/>they had been some 14 years up there!
<lb/>Their names were <persName>Juma bin Saide</persName> 
<lb/>and <persName>Amar b<subst><del>e</del><add place="over-text">i</add></subst>n Saleme</persName> -</p>
<lb/><p><orgName>Slaving</orgName> in the only trade on <placeName><geogName type="lake">Nyasa</geogName></placeName>
<lb/>at present - population prodigious -
<lb/>the <term type="occupation">bishop</term> is in the heart of the <orgName>slavery</orgName>
<lb/>when I went up to the highlands with<!-- geog: Highlands of Lake Nyassa -->
<lb/>him I met <placeName><settlement type="town"><choice><orig>Tette</orig><reg>Tete</reg></choice></settlement></placeName> people coming with
<lb/>84 captives - they fled &amp; left these
<lb/>and many others in my hand so
<lb/>I gave them over to the <orgName>mission</orgName> &amp;
<lb/>may get into a scrape for it. The

	<pb facs="liv_001693_0004" n="0004"/>
<!-- This is an address under Livingstone's text here, in another hand. It appears that Livingstone wrote this letter over a piece of paper that was originally written to him. The first line of the undertext reads "Dr. Livingstone" but we have been unable to read the rest of it. AW -->
<lb/><term type="people">Portuguese</term> had employed a tribe called 
<lb/><term type="tribe">Ajawa</term> to hunt <orgName>slaves</orgName> for them - as all
<lb/>the <term type="occupation">bishop</term>'s people were fleeing I went to
<lb/>try and induce the <term type="tribe">Ajawa</term> to give it up.
<lb/>They got but 2 fathoms for a man &amp; 1 for 
<lb/>a woman - but we came as they were
<lb/>in the act of burning three villages and
<lb/>attacked us as if they meant to make
<lb/><orgName>slaves</orgName> of us.  We had to drive them off -
<lb/>The <term type="occupation">bishop</term> has been at them since fighting 
<lb/>and intending to fight like a brick - I
<lb/><choice><sic>dont</sic><corr>don't</corr></choice> know how this will go down
<lb/>at home - I am in for a share of the
<lb/>blame - We found no difficulty in <w>collec<supplied>-</supplied>
<lb break="no"/>-tive</w> <term type="plant">cotton</term> at a cheap rate though it was
<lb/>not the season but our ship <subst><del><gap extent="1" unit="chars"/></del><add place="over-text">is</add></subst> much
<lb/>too long and deep so our opertations
<lb/>have been confined to a <measure>few miles</measure>
<lb/>if we get out little steamer on the Lake<!-- geog: Lake Nyassa -->
<lb/>the area will be increased -</p>
<lb/><p>We hear from <persName>M<hi rend="sup underline">s</hi> Burrup</persName> who arrived
<lb/>on <date when="1861-11-13">13<hi rend="sup underline">th</hi></date> that <persName>May</persName> had remained with you
<lb/>till lately - you must make out a bill
<lb/>against the Expedition and I shall get it 
<lb/>paid - <space extent="1" unit="chars"/>I am &amp;c <persName>David Livingstone</persName></p>
            </div>
